Old French <i>tison</i> ‘piece of wood’ and ‘firebrand’, in the latter sense perhaps denoting someone with a fiery temperament.","French (Nord and Pas-de-Calais): ethnic name from a derivative of Old French <i>teis</i> ‘German, Flemish’, from ancient Germanic <i>theod</i> ‘people’. Compare   Teson   and   Tesson  .","Possibly also an Americanized form of German   Theissen   or   Theisen  . Compare   Tyson  ."],"variants":[{"name":"Tesson","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  French Arnaud, Elmire, Gaston, Pierre.","French (mainly Vendée and Normandy): from <i>tesson</i>, a dialect word meaning ‘badger’, applied as a nickname for someone thought to resemble the animal in some way.","Altered form of French   Tison  . Compare   Teson  ."]},{"name":"Teson","meanings":["Altered form of French   Tison  . Compare   Tesson  ."]}]},{"name":"Gilbert","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Old French name of Germanic (Frankish) origin, derived from <i>gisil</i> ‘pledge’ + <i>berht</i> ‘bright, famous’. It was adopted by the Normans and introduced by them to Britain. This was the name of the founder of the only native British religious order (abolished at the Dissolution of the Monasteries),  St Gilbert  of Sempringham (  ?1083–1189 ), in whose honour it is still sometimes bestowed, especially among Roman Catholics. It gained a wider currency in the 19th century."],"variants":[]}],"historicEvents":[{"id":1705182,"age":6,"year":"1066","julianDay":2110409,"title":"Battle of Hastings","description":"Battle of Hastings was fought between the Norman-French army and the battle-wary English army on October 14, 1066. Duke William of Normandy believed he was the rightful king rather than Harold, who had been crowned king several months earlier. Harold was killed in battle and William was crowned king on Christmas Day 1066.","url":"https://www.english-heritage.org.uk/learn/1066-and-the-norman-conquest/what-happened-battle-hastings/","urlTitle":"English Heritage - Battle of Hastings","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705183,"age":26,"year":"1086","julianDay":2117714,"title":"Domesday Book","description":"Domesday Book is Britain's earliest extant public record with information containing land surveys and landholdings commissioned by William I. The book was completed in 1086.","url":"https://www.nationalarchives.gov.uk/domesday/","urlTitle":"National Archives - Domesday","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705184,"age":36,"year":"1096","julianDay":2121366,"title":"The Crusades","description":"A series of religious wars between Christians and Muslims, known as the Crusades, occurred between 1096 and 1291, and played a large role in European Christian dominance in the Middle East.","url":"https://www.history.com/topics/middle-ages/crusades","urlTitle":"History - The Crusades","jurisdictionLevel":2},{"id":1705185,"age":46,"year":"1106","julianDay":2125018,"title":"The Battle of Tichebray","description":"King Henry I defeated and captured his brother, Robert of Normandy, at the Battle of Tinchebray in 1106. Robert remained in captivity until his death in 1134.","jurisdictionLevel":2}],"lifeSummary":"Gilbert Tison was born about 1060, in Normandy, France. He had at least 1 son with Unknown. He died about 1124, in Malton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom, at the age of 66."},"et":{"about 1060–about 1124":"umbes 1060–umbes 1124","–Female":"Surnud","1095–1159":"1095–1159","1060–1124":"1060–1124","about 1060":"umbes 1060","1106":"1106","about 1095":"umbes 1095","1159":"1159","1124":"1124","1066":"1066","1086":"1086","about 1124":"umbes 1124","1096":"1096","1095":"1095","1060":"1060","1070":"1070","Devizes, Wiltshire, England":"Devizes, Wiltshire, England","Normandy, France":"Normandie, Prantsusmaa","Malton, Yorkshire, England, United Kingdom":"Malton, Yorkshire, Inglismaa, United Kingdom","Devizes, Wiltshire, England, United Kingdom":"Devizes, Wiltshire, Inglismaa, United Kingd